Excellent set of specs — these are calm and utilitarian, exactly what you want for any professional training context. They’ll translate well across PDF, web, or internal wiki stylesheets.

To hand your designer something literal, you can use a simple CSS‑style block that mirrors those visual priorities. It’ll work as a reference even if you’re not publishing online:

```css
/* === Training Manual Core Styles === */

/* Base layout */
body {
  font-family: 'Open Sans', 'Lato', 'Noto Sans', sans-serif;
  font-size: 16px;
  line-height: 1.35;
  color: #222;               /* soft black for readability */
  background-color: #ffffff;
  margin: 1in 1in;
}

/* Table cells */
td, th {
  padding: 10px;
  vertical-align: top;
  border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;
}

/* Alternating row background */
tr:nth-child(even) {
  background-color: #FAFAFA;
}

/* Tone column */
.tone {
  text-transform: small-caps;
  color: #555;
  font-weight: 600;
}

/* Phrase emphasis */
.phrase {
  font-weight: 700;
  color: #111;
}

/* Section labels */
.label {
  font-weight: 700;
  color: #444;
}

/* Emotion tag italics */
.emotion { font-style: italic; }

/* Sidebar (hotline block) */
.sidebar {
  background-color: #E5F3F3;   /* gentle teal */
  padding: 12px;
  font-size: 14px;
  color: #111;
  border-left: 3px solid #9ACBCC;
}
```

Your designer can drop this into any HTML, slide deck, or document editor that supports style sheets, and tweak the color variables for dark/light modes.

